solution.text:
\textbf{When are LS and MLE the same?}

\par\textbf{Step 1: Key condition.}
They are the same for $(a,b)$ when the log-likelihood is (up to constants) a \emph{decreasing function}
of the sum of squared residuals:
\[
\ell(a,b) = C - c\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i-(a+bx_i))^2
\quad\text{for some }c>0.
\]
This happens under the normal error model (and more generally, any model where the likelihood depends on $(a,b)$
only through squared residuals with a constant scale factor).

\par\textbf{Step 2: Standard textbook sufficient conditions.}
A common sufficient set is:
\[
\varepsilon_i \stackrel{\text{i.i.d.}}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2)
\quad\text{(homoskedastic normal errors),}
\]
with $x_i$ treated as fixed (or independent of $\varepsilon_i$).

\par\textbf{Conclusion.}
\[
\boxed{
\text{Least squares estimates minimize SSE and yield }
\hat b=\frac{\sum (x_i-\bar x)(y_i-\bar y)}{\sum (x_i-\bar x)^2},
\ \hat a=\bar y-\hat b\bar x.
}
\]
\[
\boxed{
\text{Under i.i.d. normal errors with common variance, MLE for $(a,b)$ equals LS.}
}
\]

