solution.text:
\textbf{Convention.}
Assume variables are centered (mean $0$) so we can omit intercepts, and assume
$\mathrm{Var}(X_1),\mathrm{Var}(X_2)>0$.

\par\textbf{Step 1: Write the population normal equations for the joint regression.}

The OLS coefficients $(a_1,a_2)$ satisfy the orthogonality (normal) equations:
\[
\mathbb{E}\big[X_1(Y-a_1X_1-a_2X_2)\big]=0,\qquad
\mathbb{E}\big[X_2(Y-a_1X_1-a_2X_2)\big]=0.
\]
Equivalently,
\[
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathbb{E}[X_1^2] & \mathbb{E}[X_1X_2]\\
\mathbb{E}[X_1X_2] & \mathbb{E}[X_2^2]
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} a_1\\ a_2\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathbb{E}[X_1Y]\\
\mathbb{E}[X_2Y]
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
So in general,
\[
(a_1,a_2) \text{ depends on both } X_1 \text{ and } X_2 \text{ jointly.}
\]

\par\textbf{Step 2: Compute the first-step coefficient $b_1$.}

Regressing $Y$ on $X_1$ alone gives
\[
b_1=\frac{\mathrm{Cov}(X_1,Y)}{\mathrm{Var}(X_1)}
=\frac{\mathbb{E}[X_1Y]}{\mathbb{E}[X_1^2]}.
\]
The corresponding residual is
\[
R_Y = Y - b_1 X_1.
\]
By construction,
\[
\mathbb{E}[X_1R_Y]=0,
\]
i.e.\ $R_Y$ is orthogonal to $X_1$.

\par\textbf{Step 3: Compute the second-step coefficient $b_2$.}

Regressing $R_Y$ on $X_2$ alone gives
\[
b_2=\frac{\mathrm{Cov}(X_2,R_Y)}{\mathrm{Var}(X_2)}
=
\frac{\mathbb{E}[X_2(Y-b_1X_1)]}{\mathbb{E}[X_2^2]}
=
\frac{\mathbb{E}[X_2Y]-b_1\mathbb{E}[X_1X_2]}{\mathbb{E}[X_2^2]}.
\]

\par\textbf{Step 4: Why the two-step procedure is generally \emph{not} equal to joint OLS.}

Joint OLS chooses $(a_1,a_2)$ so that the final residual
\[
u:=Y-a_1X_1-a_2X_2
\]
is orthogonal to \emph{both} regressors:
\[
\mathbb{E}[X_1u]=0,\qquad \mathbb{E}[X_2u]=0.
\]

But the two-step method guarantees:
\begin{itemize}
\item after step 1, $R_Y$ is orthogonal to $X_1$;
\item after step 2, the new residual $R_Y-b_2X_2$ is orthogonal to $X_2$;
\end{itemize}
it does \emph{not} generally force the final residual to remain orthogonal to $X_1$,
because $X_2$ may have a component along $X_1$.

In short: subtracting $b_2X_2$ can reintroduce correlation with $X_1$ when $X_1$ and $X_2$ are correlated.

Therefore, in general,
\[
\boxed{(a_1,a_2)\neq (b_1,b_2).}
\]

\par\textbf{Step 5: Condition for equality.}

A sufficient and essentially necessary condition (in the usual non-degenerate case) is
\[
\boxed{\mathrm{Cov}(X_1,X_2)=0 \quad (\text{orthogonality of regressors}).}
\]

\par\textbf{Step 5a: Show equality when $\mathrm{Cov}(X_1,X_2)=0$.}

If $\mathbb{E}[X_1X_2]=0$, the joint normal equations decouple:
\[
\mathbb{E}[X_1^2]\,a_1=\mathbb{E}[X_1Y],
\qquad
\mathbb{E}[X_2^2]\,a_2=\mathbb{E}[X_2Y].
\]
Hence
\[
a_1=\frac{\mathbb{E}[X_1Y]}{\mathbb{E}[X_1^2]}=b_1.
\]
Also,
\[
b_2=\frac{\mathbb{E}[X_2Y]-b_1\mathbb{E}[X_1X_2]}{\mathbb{E}[X_2^2]}
=
\frac{\mathbb{E}[X_2Y]}{\mathbb{E}[X_2^2]}
=a_2.
\]
So
\[
\boxed{\mathrm{Cov}(X_1,X_2)=0 \ \Rightarrow\ (a_1,a_2)=(b_1,b_2).}
\]

\par\textbf{Step 5b: Geometric interpretation.}
OLS is orthogonal projection of $Y$ onto the span $\mathrm{span}\{X_1,X_2\}$.
The sequential method is projection onto $X_1$ first, then onto $X_2$.
Sequential orthogonal projections equal the joint projection \emph{only when the directions are orthogonal}
(i.e. $X_1\perp X_2$).

\par\textbf{Step 6: When the two-step method \emph{can} be made equivalent (Frisch--Waugh--Lovell).}

If instead you do:
\begin{enumerate}
\item regress $Y$ on $X_1$ and take residual $R_Y$;
\item regress $X_2$ on $X_1$ and take residual $R_{X_2}$;
\item regress $R_Y$ on $R_{X_2}$;
\end{enumerate}
then the resulting coefficient on $R_{X_2}$ equals the joint OLS coefficient $a_2$.
This is the Frisch--Waugh--Lovell (partialling-out) theorem.

\par\textbf{Conclusion.}
\[
\boxed{
\text{In general } (a_1,a_2)\neq(b_1,b_2).
\text{ They are equal when } \mathrm{Cov}(X_1,X_2)=0 \text{ (orthogonal regressors).}
}
\]
Moreover, the correct sequential procedure that always matches joint OLS is the FWL residualization method.

