solution.text:
\textbf{Step 1: Why the usual \(t\)-theory fails.}

\par

In ordinary regression, the \(t\)-statistic for a coefficient estimate has an asymptotic normal or Student-\(t\) distribution under standard regularity conditions.

However, in the ADF setting, under the null hypothesis \(H_0:\phi=1\), the regressor \(X_{t-1}\) is itself nonstationary. In fact, under the null it behaves like a random walk.

Because of this:

\begin{itemize}
\item the usual law of large numbers and central limit arguments do not apply in the standard way,
\item the estimator of \(\gamma\) has a nonstandard limiting distribution,
\item the usual \(t\)-statistic is \emph{not} \(t\)-distributed.
\end{itemize}

\par

\textbf{Step 2: What distribution is used instead?}

\par

The ADF test statistic has a \textbf{Dickey--Fuller distribution}, which is a special nonstandard distribution derived under the unit root null.

Its exact form depends on which regression specification is used:

\begin{itemize}
\item no intercept,
\item intercept only,
\item intercept and deterministic trend.
\end{itemize}

So the critical values are not taken from the standard \(t\)-table. Instead, one uses
\[
\boxed{\text{Dickey--Fuller critical values}}
\]
(or more generally MacKinnon approximate critical values commonly reported in software).

Thus,
\[
\boxed{
\text{The ADF statistic does not follow a standard }t\text{-distribution; it follows a Dickey--Fuller type distribution.}
}
\]

This is important because many statistical methods assume stationarity.

\par

\textbf{Step 1: Why stationarity matters.}

\par

For a stationary series:

\begin{itemize}
\item the mean is stable over time,
\item the variance is stable over time,
\item autocovariances depend only on lag.
\end{itemize}

This makes model estimation, forecasting, and inference meaningful.

If a series is nonstationary, these properties fail, and naive statistical analysis can be misleading.

\par

\textbf{Step 2: Practical issue with stock prices.}

\par

Stock prices are often modeled approximately as random walks or near-random walks, so they are typically nonstationary.

If one regresses one nonstationary price series on another, one can easily get:

\begin{itemize}
\item high \(R^2\),
\item significant \(t\)-statistics,
\item seemingly strong relationships,
\end{itemize}

even when the relationship is spurious.

This is called \textbf{spurious regression}.

\par

\textbf{Step 3: Why returns are different.}

\par

Financial \emph{returns} are usually much closer to stationary than price levels. For that reason:

\begin{itemize}
\item stock prices are often differenced or transformed into returns,
\item models are typically fit to returns rather than raw prices,
\item forecasting and inference become much more reliable.
\end{itemize}

\par

\textbf{Step 4: Financial interpretation.}

\par

If prices have a unit root, then shocks to prices are permanent. If returns are stationary, then returns fluctuate around a stable mean structure.

Thus stationarity testing helps determine:

\begin{itemize}
\item whether differencing is needed,
\item whether level regressions are valid,
\item what forecasting model is appropriate.
\end{itemize}

So the practical importance is:

\[
\boxed{
\text{Testing stationarity helps prevent spurious inference and guides whether to model prices in levels or returns.}
}
\]

