solution.text:
In the one-shot game, cooperation does not survive because defection is a dominant strategy.

However, cooperation may emerge in a repeated setting.

\par

\textbf{Step 1: Repeated interaction.}

\par

If the prisoners interact repeatedly rather than only once, then current defection can be punished in future rounds.

For example, under a strategy such as \emph{Tit-for-Tat} or a \emph{grim trigger} strategy:

\begin{itemize}
\item cooperate as long as the other player cooperates,
\item if the other player defects, punish by defecting in future periods.
\end{itemize}

This creates an incentive to cooperate today in order to preserve future gains from cooperation.

\par

\textbf{Step 2: Importance of patience.}

\par

Cooperation is more likely when players care sufficiently about the future, i.e. when the discount factor \(\delta\) is high.

Intuitively:

\begin{itemize}
\item if players are very patient, the long-run loss from triggering future punishment can outweigh the short-run gain from a one-time defection;
\item if players are impatient, they may prefer the immediate gain from defecting.
\end{itemize}

\par

\textbf{Step 3: Other factors that support cooperation.}

\par

Cooperation may also emerge when:

\begin{itemize}
\item the game is repeated many times or indefinitely,
\item players can observe past actions,
\item there is credible punishment for defection,
\item the same players expect to meet again,
\item reputation matters.
\end{itemize}

So, in summary,
\[
\boxed{
\text{Cooperation can emerge in repeated games when future interaction and credible punishment make cooperation sustainable.}
}
\]

