solution.text:
For a \emph{long} option position:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Gamma} is usually positive,
\item \textbf{Theta} is usually negative.
\end{itemize}

\par

\textbf{What positive Gamma means.}

\par

Positive Gamma means the option's Delta adjusts favorably when the stock moves:

\begin{itemize}
\item if the stock rises, Delta increases,
\item if the stock falls, Delta decreases.
\end{itemize}

This convexity is valuable because large stock moves tend to help a long option position.

So positive Gamma means the option benefits from volatility and curvature.

\par

\textbf{What negative Theta means.}

\par

Theta measures sensitivity to the passage of time:
\[
\Theta = \frac{\partial V}{\partial t}.
\]

For a long option, Theta is typically negative, meaning that as time passes (with everything else unchanged), the option loses value.

This is time decay.

\par

\textbf{The trade-off.}

\par

A long option gives you positive Gamma, which is valuable because it provides convex exposure to stock moves. But you pay for this convexity through negative Theta, meaning the position loses value over time if the stock does not move enough.

So the basic trade-off is:

\[
\boxed{
\text{Long options have positive Gamma (good for large moves) but negative Theta (they decay with time).}
}
\]

Equivalently:

\begin{itemize}
\item If you want curvature and volatility exposure, you usually must accept time decay.
\item If you collect time decay (positive Theta), you usually must accept negative Gamma.
\end{itemize}

This is why short-option positions often earn Theta but are exposed to adverse convexity, while long-option positions enjoy convexity but pay carry.

