solution.text:
Several model extensions were developed specifically because Black--Scholes cannot reproduce smile/skew patterns.

Two important examples are:

\par

\textbf{1. Stochastic volatility models}

\par

In these models, volatility itself is random and evolves over time. A classic example is the Heston model.

This helps produce:

\begin{itemize}
\item volatility clustering,
\item changing variance levels,
\item skew/smile effects in option prices.
\end{itemize}

\par

\textbf{2. Local volatility models}

\par

In these models, volatility is a deterministic function of stock price and time:
\[
\sigma = \sigma(S,t).
\]

This allows the model to fit the observed implied volatility surface exactly at a given date.

\par

\textbf{3. Jump-diffusion models}

\par

Another major extension is to allow discrete jumps in the stock price in addition to continuous diffusion. For example, the Merton jump-diffusion model.

Jumps help capture:

\begin{itemize}
\item crash risk,
\item fat tails,
\item option smile effects.
\end{itemize}

